entry.content:
Now `TransformTree::AnchorPositionOffset()` doesn't consider `snap_amount`. Should we do the same as `TransformTree::StickyPositionOffset()` like the following?

```
  gfx::PointF scroll_position = transform_node->scroll_offset;
  if (transform_node->scrolls) {
    // The scroll position does not include snapping which shifts the scroll
    // offset to align to a pixel boundary, we need to manually include it here.
    // In this case, snapping is caused by a scroll.
    scroll_position -= transform_node->snap_amount;
  }
```

However, if we do this, we'll expose an issue if `AnchorPositionScrollData::adjustment_container_ids` references a transform node that appears later in the transform tree than the anchor-position transform node. `snap_amount` of the later transform node may be stale when we update the transform node for the anchor position. Is this a big deal?

The forward referencing issue also happens in crrev.com/c/5297007 for sticky containers (b/40947467), but `snap_amount` looks more complex because it depends on `to_screen` and `from_screen` which can depend on ancestor anchor positions (thus we can't simply do a two-pass update). The simplest way seems to accept imperfect stale `snap_amount` on a later transform node.
